# Multi-Profile App Locker — Project Overview

Flutter app for Android: two partners on the same device lock their own apps with separate PINs.
Flutter handles UI, Kotlin handles background services (foreground service, usage stats, overlay).

## Tech Stack

- Flutter (Dart) — UI and app logic
- Kotlin — Native Android (foreground service, usage stats, overlay)
- Riverpod — State management
- sqflite — Local database
- Platform Channels — Flutter ↔ Kotlin communication
- SharedPreferences — Shared data between Flutter and native service

## Folder Structure

- `lib/features/{feature_name}/` — feature screens, with optional `widgets/` subfolder
- `lib/shared/widgets/` — reusable widgets
- `lib/models/` — data models
- `lib/services/` — service classes
- `lib/core/constants/` — AppColors, AppStrings, AppDimensions
- `android/app/src/main/kotlin/com/multiprofilelock/` — native Kotlin files

## General Always

- Use Riverpod for state management, never setState except simple local UI
- Use async/await, never .then() callbacks
- Handle all errors with try/catch and show user-friendly messages
- Use named routes for all navigation
- Keep widgets small and single responsibility
- Use const constructors wherever possible
- All colors from AppColors, all strings from AppStrings, all spacing from AppDimensions
- Hash PINs using SHA-256 before storing — never store plain text PINs
- Every new file must have a top comment explaining its purpose

## General Never

- Never store plain text PINs
- Never use var when type can be inferred or explicit
- Never use dynamic types unless absolutely necessary
- Never put business logic inside UI widgets
- Never call platform channels directly from UI — go through a service
- Never hardcode package names, colors, strings, or dimensions
- Never use print() — use debugPrint()
